         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... together with the monk Ajita, to beg for alms in the house of Citraratha</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(Metr)ak and Ajita, young and attractive monks like ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Thereupon his sorrow came to the fore, and with a worried mind (to the venerable) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... of me, a person without status, when today on the glorious eighth day, young monks ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... among the old ones homage to the old means great glory; young, empty, (attractive) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Then the venerable Metrak having noted Citraratha's sorrow, to Ajita ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... those having left the house, wanting salvation, the (old ones) ..., the disciples of the Buddha ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">having left the house, wanting salvation, he will be a disciple of the Buddha....</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Having left the house in the wish for salvation, he will be a disciple of the Buddha.  (cf 197)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>629</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">is (in a position) to receive every day the homage to the Stūpa consisting of 400,000 [coins]. What is the problem? Young ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... says: This being the case, you pronounce now for him the Law, so that he is in everything together ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Then he is to be controlled by Buddha-god the teacher, not by us. || Then Citraratha, having come close, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">with a (worried) mind having made only some weak gesture of veneration, says: Go inside ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">pointing with his ﬁnger, says: Sit down! Thereupon, an inferior servant indeed ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">having brought (?) without the due respect combined with ..., he sits down by himself ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">having received ..., and having brieﬂy proclaimed some basic teaching of the Law to Citraratha, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">I am today on the glorious eighth day without status. Why?</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels">MaitrHami 3, 11-12?; MaitrSiŋgim</note><note type="remarks">This fragment contains part of the third act of the Maitreyasamitināṭaka; Uy. parallels are MaitrHami 3, 11b(?)-12b(?) and MaitrSiŋgim, Taf. 25+49 (<bibl><title corresp="ref:tekin1980"/><citedRange>222</citedRange></bibl>). See also <bibl><title corresp="ref:pinault1999"/><citedRange>196-7</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note type="remarks">The translation and the following commentary are adapted from <bibl><title corresp="ref:jietal1998"/><citedRange>198</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Cf. Uyghur text, Turfan version, Taf. 99, "Rückseite" (but to be turned over) = recto, lines 4-5 (<bibl><title corresp="ref:tekin1980"/><citedRange>225</citedRange></bibl>). For this leaf, there is no matching text in the Hami version of <hi>Maitrisimit</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:tekin1980"/><citedRange>225</citedRange></bibl>, Taf. 99, recto, lines 7-9.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:tekin1980"/><citedRange>221</citedRange></bibl>, Taf. 92, verso, lines 4-7.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Cf. Taf. 99, "Vorderseite" (but to be turned over) = verso, lines 3-7 (<bibl><title corresp="ref:tekin1980"/><citedRange>224</citedRange></bibl>).</note></p>
         </div>
